When you can’t run, cycle.
When you can’t cycle, swim.
When it's too flipping cold - walk.

Fortunately, my body seems to tolerate hill walking at the moment, after another 6 weeks off running and a 24-hour ECG for extra fun. And then I noticed on my wall chart that I have less than 20 Wainwrights to go.

For those who don’t know, the Wainwrights are a collection of 214 hills in the Lake District, immortalised by legendary fellwalker and writer Alfred Wainwright. I’ve been half-heartedly ticking them off since 2010 and once you start you can't stop. So it's about time I got the job done. 

One of the final few summits is ‘Great Cockup’ in the Northern Fells, which naturally seemed like a fitting finale to my Wainwright journey and 2022. Honestly, Google it (or actually... don't).

Anyone is welcome to join me for the final stroll on Great Cockup, sometime over Christmas. It can only go well, right?

Being able to share my experiences to help people through their own challenges is a privilege I can't take for granted. I’ve been lucky to work with incredibly bright people and organisations this year, and as a stammering 27-year-old the imposter syndrome is never lost on me. To 'burn off' a mince pie you need to run: 

Nowhere. 

Just the annual reminder that we don't need to 'earn' fuel. Our bodies are a lot smarter than that. Christmas can be stressful enough with an advent calendar of triggers, especially for anyone struggling with mental health or addiction. Modern culture almost enforces the idea of celebration and indulgence – only to punish and shame us with how many minutes or miles we’ll need to ‘burn it all off’.

To be honest, I've fallen into the same trap. My usual Christmas routine is a fast Parkrun + 20 miles or so on the trails. Largely for the love of being out, but there's always a niggling pressure to find some kind of balance and compensation. This year will be a massive test without it. When you’re unable to exercise, you realise how unhealthy this relationship with food is.

What we do most days of the year is far more important than a few days of the year. So enjoy yourselves, if you want to, or treat it like any other day. Never let others' expectations decide for you.

Life is what happens to you when you're busy making other plans.

It's that time again and on reflection, I fell short on lots of my goals last year. It’s easy to use the years gone by as the benchmark of progress - but that assumes we have the same capacity to start with, when there's so many other things outside of our control.

Last April I remember having coffee with my friend James, the day after running 105 miles around the Lakes (did I mention that already? 😂), and telling him my plans for a much bigger summer challenge. I was seriously worried whether I could pull it all together and hit the fundraising target in a short time.

Little did I know that catching Covid the next day, and the subsequent 8 month rollercoaster with Long Covid and anxiety would make the decision for me.

Progress is less about the plan: it’s what we do when things DON’T go to plan. It was an opportunity to focus energy on other areas, get some uncomfortable stuff out of the box, and build a foundation for a bigger 2023: even the menial stuff like moving house. 

Planning the year ahead is always an exciting process.  Not sure what the 'comeback' will look like yet. Right now I'm resting for 4 weeks after surgery, but if I’ve learnt one thing from 2022, then sometimes we need to slow down to speed up. And always make time for coffee with your friends. Bring it on, 2023!

10 days post-surgery. Side effects include: 

- Mountain withdrawal: luckily the recent weather has made it easier, but it didn’t take long to start itching for the hills. I can't make plans yet, though I may have made enquiries for a big mountain expedition later this year…

- Decreased mental well-being: this was almost inevitable, but super lucky to have friends checking in with me, physically and virtually. You know who you are. Who knew laughing hurts with a scar across your abs? Also grateful for a garden to get some sunlight - elusive but even more important this time of year.

- Increased productivity: I’ve got more work and admin done in the last week than I would in a month. 2023 planning almost done and even finished my tax return in my fastest known time!

- High levels of gratitude: this should only be a few weeks, for the NHS sorting the hernia, for where I live and the simple things like a proper coffee machine.

“Who are you going with?”

It's usually the first question when travelling solo. Sometimes a lack of confidence, fear of being lonely or knowing where to start put people off. 

Sharing adventures with others and building community adds so much. But there’s so many benefits to going it alone and getting to know ourselves. We don’t realise what we’re capable of until we have nobody else to call on and any drama is either created or fixed by us. Like negotiating a pot noodle in a rural Tibetan teahouse with a calculator and zero English spoken.

I’ve been fortunate to travel to some amazing places, and going solo has been the preferred style for lots of my own challenges. Maybe I’m just rubbish company. 

Obviously, right now a lot of people will have much bigger concerns than planning solo trips across the world. But solo adventures closer to home and on a daily basis are a great place to start. 

I wrote a blog for @ordnancesurvey with tips for planning a solo adventure in 2023, where to start and staying safe. Link in the usual place.

February goals: Finish the Wainwrights!

The final 7 of 214 summits eluded me before my operation in December, so the final walk will now be in the Northern Fells on Saturday 25th February. Everyone is welcome to join me.

How’s your 2023 goals going? If you've fallen off the bandwagon already, here’s a few questions to ask:

- Why do I want this? 
If your goals don't really excite or scare you, they probably won't drive you forwards for long.

- What would success look like? 
Get really specific – ‘run a sub-4 marathon’ instead of ‘getting fitter’, which is too vague and lacks direction.

- What’s the first step? 
Taking action creates motivation and inspires more action. Don’t wait for it to magically appear. 

- What are the milestones? 
Breaking goals into small steps makes them less overwhelming. I haven't ran a marathon, but I have ran a mile, 26.2 times...

- Who's holding me accountable? 
... Let me know your goals in the comments ;-)

"Listen to your body"

It’s something athletes hear all the time. With experience you get pretty tuned into when to push and when to pull back, what your body responds well to, and the fine line between a stress response and an injury that’s going to sideline you. Sometimes we get it wrong too.

Pain is there for a reason: a warning sign to back off. After my hernia operation I often did too much too soon and things hurt immediately. Like driving nearly 4 hours to a speaking event. My helicopter pilot was on strike that day 🤣

With Long Covid, it’s like spilling your brew all over your laptop keyboard. Nothing makes sense anymore. There’s faulty signals firing everywhere and the warning signs usually come a day or two later. The fear of trying and relapsing reinforces a negative feedback loop. And if we never try… you know the rest.

So now it’s time to try. Only I can fix this. Day 5 of Couch to 100 miles. Onwards!

"You get what you give."

Yesterday I spoke to a group of 6th Form students on mental health and why small acts of kindness are scientifically proven to boost our well-being.

During my #ClimbTheUK challenge in 2017, one of my followers came to surprise me at Stirling youth hostel with a stash of homemade flapjacks. With 85+ miles ahead I'd unknowingly set off 15 mins prior, so she drove out to find me on the road. Unfortunately my live tracker went down, so she gave up after 2 hours and posted the flapjacks to a youth hostel where I was due to stay a week later.

A chest infection then scuppered my schedule and I went straight past. 2 weeks later I arrived @yhacambridge after 110 miles in the rain to find a pack of flapjacks, a £20 charity donation, and this mystery postcard!

Never underestimate acts of kindness, however small, for giving people a boost in tough times.

And everyone needs a flapjack stalker sometimes...

A big welcome to the first CEO of @mindomountains, Ian Sansbury! 

When Chris and I founded the charity in 2020 we never imagined how big it would become. From the flagship event with @adventureuncovered to delivering 27 events last year, supporting 300+ people with their mental health, including the NHS, Police and Ambulance Service.

Leadership is about creating a vision, and building a great team to achieve it - like our wonderful trustees, team and 50+ freelance staff who continually go above and beyond. 

It’s also knowing your strengths and weaknesses, when ironically it's compromised my own mental health sometimes too. As the charity grows I'm not the right person to take it where it needs to be, so it can reach everyone who needs our help.

Feeling like a proud parent sending their kids off to start school, with less crying, but I'm super excited to see the charity grow and support even more people with Ian’s expertise. 

I’ll remain heavily involved as a trustee (and Chief Interference Officer) to support the team, tell the story and raise money through daft adventures… 

Thanks to everyone who's been part of the first chapter. Onwards!

Much-needed adventure inspiration from @mrmarkbeaumont on his Faster tour at Rheged last weekend. 

Mark is the fastest person to cycle around the world in 80 days (that's 240 miles a day... for perspective) amongst many other records. He's been a huge personal inspiration and kindly endorsed my 2nd book.

So much resonated, but a few favourite takeaways: 

- Trust the process, the bigger picture will always take care of itself. 

- Remove the faff. His team had to ensure he was on the bike by 4am, not 4:05am. That would have added an entire day to his record.

- Mark had 40 people working on his world record. He knew that if he failed, the whole team failed. 

- Good times won't last forever, but that means the bad ones won't either... 

Thanks Mark. Grab his books, talks and films if you're needing some adventure inspiration!

Back where it all began. Running with my old man!

Last March I got my Parkrun PB at Keswick and this weekend got my slowest at Fell Foot.

The plan was to keep my heart rate under 145bpm to avoid another crash of fatigue, which meant walking most of the hills. It took the discipline of Yoda not to set off chasing people like the good old days, especially when my dad overtook me in the first km. 

I hated exercise as a kid. On holiday in France my stepmum bribed me with €2 to run a mile with him. That was a lot of money back then... I hated every minute but dad inspired me to enter a 10km race for charity, and the rest is history. Dad came to watch every race since, as I happily claimed the family record at every distance from 5km to marathon, whilst he retired to become a Parkrun tourist. 

Never thought he'd beat me again, but never forget where you started.

Thought I was done with the big mountains. I changed my mind.

Stoked to join an expedition to climb Aconcagua in December. The highest peak in South America and outside of Asia, at 6,961 metres/22,837ft, with Mike Hamill @climbingthesevensummits. 

It’s not my highest altitude but it’s my first time since Cho Oyu in 2016. Last year was an opportunity to reflect on my goals, and the bug for high mountains never really went away, but the "why" did. It feels like the right time to get back in the high altitude game, put everything I’ve learnt since into practice and take @mindomountains to new heights.

I’m not even sure when I’ll be back to full training after Covid - but that’s just part of the comeback story, and hopefully helps others in a similar position. Adventure isn't about certainty. 

There's nowhere I’d rather spend Christmas than watching the stars from a tent on a big mountain. Although it'll cost me a few bottles of the finest Malbec for my poor mum.

Never stop dreaming, and never stop doing.

Anxiety and adventure aren’t an obvious combination. Climbing mountains and ultra-endurance looks like the pinnacle of strength and toughness. That’s why it’s even more important to share the struggles too.

Anxiety is situational. Sometimes going out of your comfort zone can be a lot closer to home. It can be much less obvious than the racing heart, excessive worrying, insomnia, or the false-alarm heart attacks that send you to the Docs for reassurance. It can be a crippling self-doubt and paranoia in all areas of life, until it’s hard to separate beliefs from reality. 

I couldn't always speak openly about it, until I read about another runner bravely sharing his experiences in a Guardian article, and realised I wasn't the only one.

6 years later... It's been great to share my story at events this week, and I'm looking forward to speaking at a few more during Mental Health Awareness Week (15-21st May) which is all themed on anxiety. Hopefully so others feel less alone too.

Every story matters. Thanks for the chance to share it!

Manage your energy, not just your time.

Recently some have commented on my ‘miraculous recovery’ now I’m back running in the hills, planning challenges and entering @13valleysultra when in March I could only manage 4 x 30 second jogs. Whether sceptical, curious or positive, I wanted to share a reminder in case Instagram only shows the fluffy side.

I’m still only about 50% capacity of where I was before Covid hit me in April 2022. For the last few months I’ve been gradually increasing my tolerance to exercise and finding the edges of the ‘box’. That inevitably means falling over the box too. If I do ‘too much’ I still get whacked by fatigue, headaches, palpitations, random pains all over and brain fog, in no particular order.

That’s not just too much training either. Our body only knows stress – whether that’s from training, work, travel, poor sleep. To pinch another analogy, I used to live life in 6th gear. Right now I can only manage 3rd. So I have to carefully choose where that energy goes, which means saying no more often, cancelling plans last minute, sleeping like a dog and generally feeling very unproductive. But worth it to run in the hills again.

Always be kind: you never know what people are dealing with... and you might just motivate them even more 😎

Two weeks 'til my next challenge, and six years ago today I finished Climb The UK! 

It was my second hardest and most rewarding challenge – climbing to the highest point of all 100 counties in the UK, approx 5,000 miles of cycling, walking, running (and kayaking to the Isle of Wight) in 72 days.
 
After the universe told me high-altitude wasn't my cup of coffee, there was a curiosity to find adventure closer to home. And did I find it! From the remote munros of the Scottish Highlands, to the highest point of Durham in a military firing range, or the highest point of Kent in someone’s back garden, or Nottinghamshire behind a metal fence above the M1.
 
It was relentless. Constantly racing the deadline I’d set myself, pulling out consecutive 100-mile days in torrential rain, tearing a quad muscle on day 5 and slowing down the onset of hypothermia in a phonebox. Somehow managed to deliver 6 talks at schools and conferences and attend a friends wedding along the way – that’s a level of 'winging it' I don't want to repeat!
 
The important part is what you learn and the friends you make on the way. The kindness of strangers got me around as it always does. I can't possibly tag you all. In the last 2 weeks alone I’ve spent time with 5 of those friends here in the Lakes.

It raised £25,000 for Young Minds UK, but it took longer to get an appointment for my mental health than it did to cycle 5,000 miles. And @mindomountains was born a year later.

Thanks to everyone who's followed me ever since. Until next time!

A 16-month battle ensued as the inov-8 ambassador fought to regain his physical and mental wellbeing.

“Fortunately, these were mild compared to some - but unlike usual injuries there was no protocol, no timescale and no guarantee.

4 tips for recovery after endurance events 👇

It's more than 3 weeks since the Frog Graham and recovery has gone pretty well. Now ready to go again @13valleysultra 100km in less than 4 weeks time! Here's my approach: 

1️⃣ Fuelling. The simplest yet the hardest part for me. With my past eating disorder the natural reflex is over-restricting once I've stopped moving and spent a day eating flapjacks. In reality we should be doing the opposite. What I do now is allow myself a week of eating whatever I feel like, no counting, ensuring quality fresh food and anti-inflammatory stuff too (yes 'lots of protein') and listening to body signals. It takes much longer with an energy deficit!

2️⃣ Down time. Don't underestimate mental fatigue too. I struggle to think clearly or make basic decisions for a few days. I always schedule some time alone with absolutely nothing on the agenda - to sit by a tarn aimlessly and watch the world/Swans go by.

3️⃣ Reflect. Whilst fresh in mind I write a review of everything that went well and a (longer) list of what to improve. Sorting through photos and writing a diary helps process it mentally.

4️⃣ Keep moving. Obviously depends how broken you are but this generally speeds up the process. Cold water was amazing for flushing out sore quads and knees after the Frog. I always take at least a week of doing whatever I feel like, trying to ignore the watch, digging the bike out of the shed and moving just for fun - not what Strava thinks.

** I'm no expert and these won't work for everyone - so would love to hear your tips below!👇

Our struggles are a gift. Our experience gives us a perspective that others don’t yet have access to - so never be afraid to share it.

Sometimes you've just got to stop thinking, put some music on and open the sodding door.

It's harder to find the motivation now the days are getting shorter and colder, and hills look more like this than epic sunrises or waterfalls.

Thing is we shouldn't be looking for motivation in the first place. It's not something we have or don't have - we have to create it ourselves.

Anyone else struggling with this right now?! A few tips... 

- Do the hardest thing first. Take advantage of energy and willpower levels when at their highest.

- Reduce decisions. Trying to choose the best route or session just creates another barrier.

- Aiming for 10 minutes is better than nothing (and once you get out, you'll probably end up going further anyway...)

- Accountability. Bring a friend. Or the dog. It's much harder to let someone else down than ourselves.

- Commitment. Set a short-term goal or habit (like @redjanuaryuk) to give you a 'why' to get out the door when you have every excuse not to.
